Formal Model Blueprint Document
Version: v1.0
Status: Research Design Blueprint
Purpose: Institutional Macro Research Stack Integration
________________________________________
1. Model Identity
Model Name: Credit Spread Regime Model
Short Name: CSRM
Version: v1.0
Model Type: Deterministic macro regime classification model
Primary Domain: Credit, macro risk, cross-asset confirmation
Primary Output: Daily macro risk regime signal for allocation and trading overlays
________________________________________
2. Model Objective
The objective of the Credit Spread Regime Model is to classify the market environment into a transparent and usable macro credit regime using market-based credit spread proxies and supporting cross-asset information.
The model is designed to detect whether credit conditions are:
•	improving
•	stable
•	deteriorating
•	deteriorating rapidly
•	recovering from stress
The model must produce outputs suitable for:
•	macro regime detection
•	equity risk filtering
•	defensive rotation overlays
•	bond/equity allocation adjustments
•	cross-asset confirmation
•	integration into a larger macro dashboard or risk-on/risk-off engine
________________________________________
3. Core Economic Logic
Credit markets often respond earlier and more directly to changes in financial stress than equities.
When credit spreads tighten or credit proxies outperform safe government bond proxies, the market is generally signaling:
•	improving liquidity conditions
•	lower default stress
•	higher risk appetite
•	a healthier macro backdrop
When credit spreads widen or credit proxies underperform safe government bond proxies, the market is generally signaling:
•	rising financial stress
•	weaker risk appetite
•	growing concern about growth, solvency, or liquidity
•	more defensive market conditions
The model formalizes this logic by measuring the relative performance and internal condition of:
•	high yield credit
•	investment grade credit
•	short-duration Treasuries
•	intermediate-duration Treasuries
•	long-duration Treasuries
•	equities
•	implied volatility
________________________________________
4. Model Use Cases
The model is intended to support the following workflows:
4.1 Macro regime detection
Identify whether the environment is Risk-On, Neutral, or Risk-Off based on credit behavior.
4.2 Portfolio overlays
Adjust gross exposure, beta posture, and defensive allocations based on the current regime.
4.3 Equity risk filtering
Use credit deterioration as a filter against adding equity risk during fragile conditions.
4.4 Cross-asset confirmation
Assess whether credit confirms or contradicts equity strength.
4.5 Trading overlays
Use regime and sub-signals to adjust position sizing, acceptable setups, and sector aggressiveness.
