8. Why SHY and VIX Are Included
8.1 Why SHY matters
SHY improves the model because it provides a short-duration Treasury anchor with minimal long-end rate distortion.
This is useful because:
•	HYG/TLT can weaken due to duration shocks rather than pure credit stress
•	HYG/IEF is better than HYG/TLT for many regimes, but still rate-sensitive
•	HYG/SHY and LQD/SHY isolate credit relative performance against a more stable safe-asset baseline
This makes SHY-based ratios useful for identifying whether true credit stress exists independent of aggressive long-duration Treasury moves.
8.2 Why VIX matters
VIX is included as a supporting stress confirmation variable, not as a primary regime driver.
It is useful because:
•	rising implied volatility often confirms deteriorating risk appetite
•	credit deterioration plus rising VIX is stronger evidence of risk-off than credit alone
•	falling VIX during improving credit conditions supports recovery or confirmed risk-on classification
VIX should not dominate the model because it is equity-volatility-specific and can overreact. It is best used as a confirmation and stress-acceleration input.
