9. Feature Layer Design
The feature layer converts raw ratios and market series into interpretable measurements.
The model should organize features into the following groups:
•	trend features
•	stress features
•	confirmation features
•	divergence features
•	persistence features
________________________________________
10. Feature Definitions
10.1 Trend features
These measure whether credit is improving or deteriorating.
For each primary proxy, calculate:
•	5-day return
•	20-day return
•	60-day return
•	distance from 20-day moving average
•	distance from 60-day moving average
•	above/below 20-day moving average flag
•	above/below 60-day moving average flag
Main purpose
Capture short-, medium-, and intermediate-horizon credit trend direction.
________________________________________
10.2 Stress features
These measure cumulative damage and instability.
For each primary proxy, calculate:
•	20-day realized volatility of daily proxy returns
•	63-day drawdown from rolling high
•	5-day deterioration rate
•	10-day deterioration rate
•	downside volatility over 20 days
•	negative streak length over recent days
Main purpose
Differentiate mild weakness from true stress.
________________________________________
10.3 Confirmation features
These measure whether credit weakness or strength is broad.
Calculate:
•	fraction of primary proxies with positive 20-day return
•	fraction of primary proxies above 20-day moving average
•	fraction of primary proxies above 60-day moving average
•	HY improving flag
•	IG improving flag
•	HY and IG both improving flag
•	HY and IG both deteriorating flag
•	JNK confirmation flag
Main purpose
Reduce noise and avoid overreacting to a single ETF or ratio.
________________________________________
10.4 Divergence features
These measure whether credit and equities are aligned.
Calculate:
•	HYG_IEF_20d_return - SPY_20d_return
•	LQD_IEF_20d_return - SPY_20d_return
•	HYG_SHY_20d_return - SPY_20d_return
•	credit weakness while SPY positive flag
•	credit improvement while SPY weak flag
•	credit weakness plus VIX rising flag
Main purpose
Identify early warning conditions and transition regimes.
________________________________________
10.5 VIX features
Because VIX is explicitly included, define a dedicated feature block:
•	VIX level
•	5-day VIX return
•	20-day VIX return
•	VIX above 20-day moving average flag
•	VIX z-score
•	VIX trend direction
•	VIX acceleration over 5 days
Main purpose
Confirm or intensify stress interpretation.
________________________________________
10.6 Persistence features
These measure whether the regime is durable.
Calculate:
•	10-day rolling average of composite score
•	5-day change in composite score
•	10-day fraction of days with positive composite score
•	10-day fraction of days with negative composite score
•	days since last regime flip
Main purpose
Reduce whipsaw and stabilize classification.
________________________________________
11. Normalization Framework
Because raw features operate on different scales, features should be normalized before scoring.
Recommended normalization methods
Primary method
Rolling z-score over a fixed lookback window
Recommended baseline:
•	60-day rolling z-score
Secondary method
Bounded directional transformations for breadth-like variables
Examples:
•	breadth fraction transformed into [-1, +1]
Stability rules
•	clip extreme z-scores
•	require minimum rolling history
•	preserve NaN where insufficient data exists
•	do not silently forward-fill core market features
________________________________________
12. Model Score Architecture
The model should use a layered score structure.
12.1 Required sub-scores
The model will compute the following five sub-scores:
A. Credit Trend Score
Measures directional improvement or deterioration in primary credit proxies.
B. Credit Stress Score
Measures drawdown, volatility, and deterioration intensity.
C. Credit Confirmation Score
Measures breadth and HY/IG agreement.
D. Credit Divergence Score
Measures whether credit confirms or contradicts equities and whether VIX confirms stress.
E. Credit Persistence Score
Measures stability and regime durability.
________________________________________
13. Sub-Score Construction Logic
13.1 Credit Trend Score
Inputs
•	normalized 20-day returns of HYG/IEF, LQD/IEF, HYG/LQD, HYG/SHY, LQD/SHY
•	normalized moving-average gaps
•	normalized 60-day returns
Interpretation
•	positive = credit improving
•	negative = credit deteriorating
________________________________________
13.2 Credit Stress Score
Inputs
•	normalized drawdowns
•	normalized realized vol
•	normalized downside vol
•	deterioration speed
•	VIX level and VIX acceleration as supporting stress confirmation
Interpretation
•	more negative = rising stress
•	less negative or positive = stress easing
Note
VIX should affect this score modestly, not dominate it.
________________________________________
13.3 Credit Confirmation Score
Inputs
•	breadth across primary proxies
•	HY and IG alignment
•	JNK confirmation
•	proportion of proxies above trend
Interpretation
•	positive = broad confirmation of improving credit
•	negative = broad confirmation of deteriorating credit
________________________________________
13.4 Credit Divergence Score
Inputs
•	credit minus SPY relative return metrics
•	credit weakness while equities rise
•	credit improvement while equities lag
•	credit weakness plus VIX rising
Interpretation
•	positive = credit supportive or stronger than equities
•	negative = warning that equities may be fragile
________________________________________
13.5 Credit Persistence Score
Inputs
•	rolling average of recent composite score
•	recent consistency of sign
•	days since last flip
•	5-day change in composite score
Interpretation
•	positive = durable trend
•	negative = persistent weakness or unstable recovery
________________________________________
14. Final Composite Score
The final composite score should be a weighted combination of the five sub-scores.
Recommended v1 weights
•	Credit Trend Score = 0.35
•	Credit Stress Score = 0.25
•	Credit Confirmation Score = 0.20
•	Credit Divergence Score = 0.10
•	Credit Persistence Score = 0.10
Reasoning
•	trend should be the dominant driver
•	stress should be the second-largest driver
•	confirmation materially improves robustness
•	divergence adds valuable warning information
•	persistence reduces whipsaw
Final scale
The final score should be bounded to:
•	-1.00 = strongest Risk-Off
•	0.00 = neutral
•	+1.00 = strongest Risk-On
________________________________________
15. Regime Classification Rules
The model must convert the continuous score into a discrete label.
Recommended regime thresholds
•	score >= +0.35 → Risk-On
•	-0.35 < score < +0.35 → Neutral
•	score <= -0.35 → Risk-Off
These thresholds should remain configurable.
________________________________________
16. Sub-Signal Flags
In addition to the main regime label, the model should output transition and warning flags.
16.1 Early Warning
Trigger when:
•	credit trend is negative or deteriorating
•	SPY remains positive or relatively firm
•	divergence score is negative
•	optional VIX confirmation strengthens the flag
Meaning
Credit is warning that equities may be underpricing risk.
________________________________________
16.2 Stress Acceleration
Trigger when:
•	stress score worsens sharply over 5 days
•	drawdowns deepen
•	volatility rises
•	VIX rises materially
•	breadth deteriorates
Meaning
Conditions are not only weak, but worsening quickly.
________________________________________
16.3 Recovery
Trigger when:
•	composite score improves meaningfully over 5 days
•	prior regime was stressed
•	HY and IG stop deteriorating
•	VIX stabilizes or declines
•	breadth improves from weak levels
Meaning
Conditions may be transitioning from stress toward normalization.
________________________________________
16.4 Confirmed Risk-On
Trigger when:
•	composite score exceeds Risk-On threshold
•	HY and IG both improving
•	breadth strong
•	divergence not negative
•	VIX not rising aggressively
Meaning
Risk appetite is broadly supported.
