21. Data Quality and Robustness Rules
The model must handle operational issues cleanly.
21.1 Missing data
•	preserve NaN where input data is unavailable
•	avoid implicit forward-filling of price series unless explicitly chosen before model entry
•	require minimum history for rolling calculations
21.2 Misaligned dates
•	align on date index before feature generation
•	allow outer alignment only if explicitly intended upstream
•	default model input should be a clean aligned daily panel
21.3 Division by zero
•	protect all ratio calculations using safe division
•	replace near-zero denominators with NaN
21.4 Insufficient history
•	rolling features should remain NaN until minimum periods are met
21.5 Stable naming
•	all columns must use deterministic, machine-safe names
•	all config thresholds should be centralized
21.6 Bad ticker data
•	model should validate required columns before execution
•	optional inputs may be bypassed if unavailable, but required inputs should raise validation errors
________________________________________
22. Configuration Framework
All model thresholds and windows should live in a single config dictionary.
Required configurable elements
•	proxy list
•	short window
•	medium window
•	long window
•	z-score window
•	vol window
•	persistence window
•	regime thresholds
•	sub-score weights
•	flag thresholds
•	minimum rolling history fraction
•	clipping bounds
This is required so the model is easy to tune, audit, and integrate into pipelines.
________________________________________
23. Recommended Baseline Parameters
These are recommended starting defaults for v1:
•	short window = 5
•	medium window = 20
•	long window = 60 or 63
•	z-score window = 60
•	vol window = 20
•	persistence window = 10
Regime thresholds
•	Risk-On = +0.35
•	Risk-Off = -0.35
Suggested flag concepts
•	early warning divergence threshold
•	stress acceleration threshold based on 5-day score decline
•	recovery threshold based on 5-day score improvement
•	confirmed risk-on breadth threshold
